Galina Starovoitova, a member of the lower house of Russia's parliament from the reformist party Democratic Russia, was attacked in an apartment building along with her aide, the Interfax news agency reported.
A liberal lawmaker who planned to run for president in Russia's next elections was shot to death Friday in St. Petersburg, police said.
Starovoitova was shot to death Friday evening as she and an aide scaled the stairs to her apartment in St. Petersburg.
She served as President Boris Yeltsin's aide on ethnic issues in 1991-92 the only woman in his immediate circle and later joined the Russian parliament as one of the most vocal defenders of liberal reforms.
Police said two men followed Starovoitova and her aide, Ruslan Linkov, 27, and shot them on the stairs of her building Friday evening.
